03/22110248/IMG_7741-2048x1367.jpg?ezimgfmt=ng:webp/ngcb8 2048w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22110248/IMG_7741-696x464.jpg?ezimgfmt=ng:webp/ngcb8 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22110248/IMG_7741-1068x713.jpg?ezimgfmt=ng:webp/ngcb8 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22110248/IMG_7741-1920x1281.jpg?ezimgfmt=ng:webp/ngcb8 1920w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22110248/IMG_7741-629x420.jpg?ezimgfmt=ng:webp/ngcb8 629w\"></a></p><h3>What is a wheel-on trainer?</h3><p>The two most popular styles of indoor trainers are direct drive and wheel-on. With direct drive, you take the rear wheel off and the trainer takes its place. The bike attaches to the trainer just like a rear wheel and uses the cassette on the flywheel as a means for pedaling. Wheel-on trainers keep the bike completely intact so it attaches to the trainer without having to remove any wheels. Resistance comes from the contact of the rear tire and the roller of the trainer.</p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22121028/IMG_7742-scaled.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22121028/IMG_7742-scaled.jpg\" alt=\"Elite Tuo Trainer Review Full Bike attached \" width=\"2560\" height=\"1709\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2560px) 100vw, 2560px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb8 src ng ngcb8 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22121028/IMG_7742-scaled.jpg\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/22121028/IMG_7742-scaled.jpg 2560w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-conte